    </ol>
  </aside>

  <div class="methodology-content">

  <!-- Prerequisites -->
  <section id="prerekvizity">
    <h2>Prerequisites</h2>

    <h3>Tools</h3>
    <div class="card">
      <table>
        <thead>
          <tr><th>Tool</th><th>Minimum version</th><th>Check</th></tr>
        </thead>
        <tbody>
          <tr><td>Python</td><td>3.10+</td><td><code>python --version</code></td></tr>
          <tr><td>PyYAML</td><td>any</td><td><code>pip install pyyaml</code></td></tr>
          <tr><td>GitHub CLI (gh)</td><td>2.40+</td><td><code>gh --version</code></td></tr>
          <tr><td>Git</td><td>2.30+</td><td><code>git --version</code></td></tr>
        </tbody>
      </table>
    </div>

    <h3>GitHub CLI scopes</h3>
    <pre><code>gh auth login
gh auth refresh -s repo,project,read:project,admin:org</code></pre>
    <p>Check:</p>
    <pre><code>gh auth status
# Must show scopes: repo, project, admin:org</code></pre>

    <h3>Organization and team</h3>
    <p>Before you start, you need:</p>
    <ul>
      <li>A GitHub organization (e.g. <code>my-org</code>)</li>
      <li>A defined team: names, roles (Arch, Dev, DevSecOps, PM, QA, BO), FTE, capacities</li>
      <li>At least a basic backlog (1 Epic, 2-3 Features, 5-10 Stories)</li>
    </ul>

    <p>
      <code>role:</code> in <code>people.yaml</code> is a free-form
      label used for reports (timesheet column, Excel exports) and as
      input to the synthetic calibration corpus. Engine signal weights
      apply uniformly regardless of a person's role &mdash;
      <code>assignee=4.0</code>, <code>pr_author=3.4</code>,
      <code>commit_author=2.78</code>, etc. are the same for everyone.
    </p>
  </section>

  <!-- Phase 1 -->
  <section id="faze-1">
    <h2>Phase 1: Infrastructure (Day 1, ~4 hours)</h2>

    <h3>Path A: Claude Code (recommended)</h3>
    <p>In a terminal with Claude Code installed:</p>
    <pre><code>/edpa setup</code></pre>
    <p>Claude Code runs steps 1.1-1.6 automatically — creates the repo, configures the team, sets up Issue Types, and creates the GitHub Project.</p>

    <h3>Path B: Manual CLI</h3>
    <p>The steps below describe the manual procedure without Claude Code.</p>

    <h3>1.1 Install the EDPA plugin</h3>
    <p><strong>Variant A: Shell installer (recommended)</strong></p>
    <pre><code>cd my-project
curl -fsSL https://edpa.technomaton.com/install.sh | sh</code></pre>
    <p><strong>Variant B: Manual copy</strong></p>
    <pre><code>cd my-project
gh repo clone technomaton/edpa /tmp/edpa
cp -r /tmp/edpa/plugin/ .claude/
rm -rf /tmp/edpa</code></pre>

    <p>Resulting structure:</p>
    <pre><code>my-project/
  .edpa/
    config.yaml          # Main configuration
    people.yaml          # Team and project
    initiatives/         # 1 file = 1 initiative
    epics/               # 1 file = 1 epic
    features/            # 1 file = 1 feature
    stories/             # 1 file = 1 story
    sync_state.json      # Last sync state
    iterations/          # Iteration plans and results
  .github/workflows/
    edpa-branch-check.yml     # CI: branch-naming check
    edpa-iteration-close.yml  # CI: iteration close (workflow_dispatch)
    edpa-sync-projects-to-git.yml   # Cron: Projects -&gt; Git (15 min)
    edpa-sync-git-to-projects.yml   # Push trigger: Git -&gt; Projects
  .claude/edpa/templates/
    people.yaml.tmpl   # Capacity-registry template
    cw_heuristics.yaml.tmpl    # CW heuristics template
    project.yaml.tmpl    # Project-config template
  .claude/edpa/scripts/
    engine.py       # EDPA computational core
    backlog.py      # Backlog management (tree, show, wsjf, validate)
    sync.py         # Bidirectional GitHub Projects &lt;-&gt; Git sync
    issue_types.py  # Issue Types management at org level
    project_setup.py      # Automated GitHub Project creation
    project_views.py      # Views setup
    create_project_views.py    # Playwright views automation (optional)
    calibrate_signals.py # CW signal-weights calibration (Monte Carlo + MAD)
  .edpa/data/              # Ground-truth data (post-PI)
  .edpa/reports/           # Generated per-iteration reports
  .edpa/snapshots/         # Frozen iteration snapshots
  docs/                  # Documentation</code></pre>

    <h3>1.2 Configure the team (people.yaml)</h3>
    <pre><code># /edpa setup generates .edpa/config/people.yaml automatically</code></pre>
    <p>Edit <code>.edpa/config/people.yaml</code>:</p>
    <pre><code>cadence:
  iteration_weeks: 2                    # 1 (AI-native) or 2 (classic)
  pi_weeks: 10                          # 5 or 10
  delivery_iterations_per_pi: 4         # PI minus IP iteration
  ip_iterations_per_pi: 1              # Innovation &amp; Planning

teams:
  - id: "My Team"
    planning_factor: 0.8               # Plan to 80% of capacity

people:
  - id: alice
    name: "Alice Smith"
    role: Arch                          # Arch, Dev, DevSecOps, PM, QA, BO
    team: "My Team"
    fte: 0.5
    capacity_per_iteration: 40          # hours (FTE x 80 for a 2-week iter.)
    email: "alice@example.com"
    availability: confirmed

  - id: bob
    name: "Bob Johnson"
    role: Dev
    team: "My Team"
    fte: 1.0
    capacity_per_iteration: 80
    email: "bob@example.com"
    availability: confirmed</code></pre>
    <div class="note"><strong>Important:</strong> <code>planning_factor</code> is a planning heuristic (plan to 80%). The EDPA engine always calculates against 100% of capacity — the buffer absorbs unplanned work.</div>
    <div class="note"><strong>Per-iteration capacity:</strong> the baseline is <code>capacity_per_iteration</code> in <code>people.yaml</code>. To adjust it for a single iteration (PTO, overtime, ramp) use the <code>/edpa:capacity &lt;iteration&gt; --add --person &lt;id&gt; --hours 20|+8|-12 --note "…"</code> command (also <code>--list</code> / <code>--remove</code>). The override is stored in the iteration YAML <code>people:</code> block and shows in the report as <code>capacity</code> / <code>capacity_baseline</code> / <code>capacity_override</code>. Closed iterations reject overrides — set them <em>before</em> closing (Stage 1 of <code>/edpa:close-iteration</code>).</div>

    <h3>1.3 Configure the project (project.yaml)</h3>
    <pre><code># /edpa setup generates .edpa/config/project.yaml automatically</code></pre>
    <p>Edit <code>.edpa/config/project.yaml</code>:</p>
    <pre><code>project:
  name: "My Project"
  registration: ""
  program: ""
  organizations:
    - name: "My Organization"
  domain: "myproject.com"

governance:
  methodology: "EDPA v{VERSION}"

naming:
  pi_pattern: "PI-&#123;year&#125;-&#123;pi_num&#125;"
  iteration_pattern: "PI-&#123;year&#125;-&#123;pi_num&#125;.&#123;iter_num&#125;"
  branch_pattern: "&#123;type&#125;/&#123;item_id&#125;-&#123;description&#125;"
  item_prefixes:
    initiative: "I"
    epic: "E"
    feature: "F"
    story: "S"
    task: "T"
    defect: "D"</code></pre>

    <h3>1.4 Configure CW heuristics</h3>
    <pre><code># /edpa setup generates .edpa/config/cw_heuristics.yaml automatically</code></pre>
    <p>Default weights in the <code>cw_heuristics.yaml.tmpl</code> template are calibrated by Monte Carlo simulation (1000 scenarios, 31 041 records, MAD = 0.0805). For most teams the defaults are fine.</p>

    <p>The engine consumes five <strong>signal weights</strong> — how much each kind of git evidence contributes to <code>contribution_score</code> on an item:</p>

    <div class="card">
      <table>
        <thead>
          <tr><th>Signal</th><th>Weight</th><th>Meaning</th></tr>
        </thead>
        <tbody>
          <tr><td><code>assignee</code></td><td>4.00</td><td>GitHub issue assignee</td></tr>
          <tr><td><code>pr_author</code></td><td>3.40</td><td>PR author referencing the item</td></tr>
          <tr><td><code>commit_author</code></td><td>2.78</td><td>Commit with S-XXX/F-XXX in branch, title, or message</td></tr>
          <tr><td><code>pr_reviewer</code></td><td>2.25</td><td>PR review submitted (excluding self)</td></tr>
          <tr><td><code>issue_comment</code></td><td>1.14</td><td>Issue/PR comment (excluding bots)</td></tr>
        </tbody>
      </table>
    </div>

    <p>Signals add up into <code>contribution_score</code> per (person, item), then normalize per-item: <code>cw = score / &Sigma;<sub>persons</sub> score</code>. Role labels (owner/key/reviewer/consulted) are derived from the dominant signal at display time only — the engine never stores or uses them for computation.</p>

    <p>Calibrate via <code>/edpa calibrate</code> — Monte Carlo random sampling + coordinate descent over the 5D signal-weights space against a synthetic corpus. See the <a href="#architektura">Architecture</a> section for details.</p>

    <h3>1.5 Configure .edpa/iterations/ and .edpa/config/edpa.yaml</h3>
    <p>From v1.5 onward, PI and iteration data live in <code>.edpa/iterations/</code> as separate files. <code>edpa.yaml</code> only carries stable governance / sync config.</p>
    <pre><code># .edpa/iterations/PI-2026-1.yaml — PI-level metadata
pi:
  id: PI-2026-1
  status: active
  iteration_weeks: 2
  pi_iterations: 5
  start_date: 2026-04-01
  end_date: 2026-06-09</code></pre>
    <pre><code># .edpa/iterations/PI-2026-1.1.yaml — per-iteration data
iteration:
  id: PI-2026-1.1
  pi: PI-2026-1
  start_date: 2026-04-01
  end_date: 2026-04-14
  weeks: 2
  status: planned
# (planning / delivery sections grow as the iteration runs)</code></pre>
    <p>Create <code>PI-2026-1.2.yaml</code> through <code>PI-2026-1.5.yaml</code> the same way; the last gets <code>type: IP</code>. Continuity is enforced by <code>validate_iterations.py</code> and the PostToolUse hook.</p>
    <pre><code># .edpa/config/edpa.yaml — sync config
sync:
  github_org: "my-org"
  github_project_number: 1
  sync_interval: "15m"
  auto_commit: true</code></pre>

    <h3>1.6 Set up Issue Types in the organization</h3>
    <p><strong>Claude Code (recommended):</strong></p>
    <pre><code>/edpa setup</code></pre>
    <p>Issue Types are created automatically as part of setup.</p>
    <p><strong>Manual CLI:</strong></p>
    <pre><code># Show current types
python3 .claude/edpa/scripts/issue_types.py list --org my-org

# Create the EDPA Issue Types set
python3 .claude/edpa/scripts/issue_types.py setup --org my-org

# Dry-run (only shows what would happen)
python3 .claude/edpa/scripts/issue_types.py setup --org my-org --dry-run</code></pre>

    <p>EDPA creates these Issue Types:</p>
    <div class="card">
      <table>
        <thead>
          <tr><th>Type</th><th>Color</th><th>Description</th></tr>
        </thead>
        <tbody>
          <tr><td>Initiative</td><td style="color:var(--pk)">PINK</td><td>Business case, investment intent</td></tr>
          <tr><td>Epic</td><td style="color:var(--ac2)">PURPLE</td><td>Strategic goal, 6-9 months</td></tr>
          <tr><td>Feature</td><td style="color:var(--cy)">BLUE</td><td>Must fit within a Planning Interval</td></tr>
          <tr><td>Story</td><td style="color:var(--gn)">GREEN</td><td>Delivered within an iteration</td></tr>
          <tr><td>Defect</td><td style="color:var(--rd)">RED</td><td>Defect in existing functionality</td></tr>
          <tr><td>Task</td><td style="color:var(--yl)">YELLOW</td><td>Technical work</td></tr>
        </tbody>
      </table>
    </div>
    <div class="note"><strong>Note:</strong> Enabler is a <strong>label</strong> (Business vs Enabler classification, SAFe), not an Issue Type.</div>

    <h3>1.7 Populate the backlog</h3>
    <p>EDPA uses a file-per-item structure — every work item is a separate YAML file:</p>
    <pre><code>.edpa/
  people.yaml
  config.yaml
  initiatives/
    I-1.yaml         # 1 file = 1 initiative
  epics/
    E-1.yaml         # 1 file = 1 epic
  features/
    F-1.yaml         # 1 file = 1 feature
  stories/
    S-1.yaml         # 1 file = 1 story
  iterations/
    PI-2026-1.1.yaml # iteration plan</code></pre>

    <p>Example story file (<code>.edpa/backlog/stories/S-1.yaml</code>):</p>
    <pre><code>id: S-1
type: Story
title: "Parser implementation"
status: Backlog
parent: F-1
js: 5
assignee: dev1
iteration: PI-2026-1.1</code></pre>

    <p>Adding a new item:</p>
    <pre><code># Claude Code:
/edpa setup    # interactively adds items

# CLI:
python3 .claude/edpa/scripts/backlog.py add --type Story --parent F-1 --title "..." --js 5 --assignee dev1
python3 .claude/edpa/scripts/backlog.py add --type Epic --title "..." --js 13 --bv 13 --tc 8 --rr 5</code></pre>

    <p>Verify integrity:</p>
    <pre><code>python3 .claude/edpa/scripts/backlog.py validate</code></pre>
    <p>Show the hierarchy:</p>
    <pre><code>python3 .claude/edpa/scripts/backlog.py tree
python3 .claude/edpa/scripts/backlog.py tree --level epic</code></pre>
    <p>Show WSJF prioritization:</p>
    <pre><code>python3 .claude/edpa/scripts/backlog.py wsjf
python3 .claude/edpa/scripts/backlog.py wsjf --level feature</code></pre>

    <h3>1.8 Create the GitHub Project</h3>
    <p><strong>Claude Code (recommended):</strong></p>
    <pre><code>/edpa setup</code></pre>
    <p>The GitHub Project is created automatically as part of setup.</p>
    <p><strong>Manual CLI:</strong></p>
    <pre><code>python3 .claude/edpa/scripts/project_setup.py \
  --org my-org \
  --repo my-project \
  --project-title "EDPA -- My Project"</code></pre>
    <p>The script performs 9 steps:</p>
    <ol>
      <li>Creates labels (Enabler)</li>
      <li>Creates GitHub Project v2 at org level</li>
      <li>Creates custom fields: Job Size, BV, TC, RR&amp;OE, WSJF Score, Team + 4 Status fields (Initiative/Epic/Feature/Story Status with SAFe workflows)</li>
      <li>Links project to repository</li>
      <li>Queries native Issue Types from organization</li>
      <li>Creates issues from item files in <code>.edpa/</code> with native Issue Types</li>
      <li>Sets field values on all project items</li>
      <li>Links sub-issues (parent-child hierarchy Initiative&rarr;Epic&rarr;Feature&rarr;Story)</li>
      <li>Updates <code>.edpa/config/edpa.yaml</code> with project number</li>
    </ol>

    <h3>1.9 Set up Project views</h3>
    <p><strong>Claude Code (recommended):</strong></p>
    <pre><code>/edpa setup</code></pre>
    <p>Views are configured automatically as part of setup.</p>
    <p><strong>Manual CLI:</strong></p>
    <p><strong>Path A: Manual setup with instructions</strong></p>
    <pre><code>python3 .claude/edpa/scripts/project_views.py instructions --org my-org --project 1</code></pre>
    <div class="card">
      <table>
        <thead>
          <tr><th>View</th><th>Type</th><th>Filter/Sort</th></tr>
        </thead>
        <tbody>
          <tr><td>All Items</td><td>Table</td><td>All items, sorted by WSJF</td></tr>
          <tr><td>Board</td><td>Board</td><td>Funnel / Analyzing / Backlog / Implementing / Done</td></tr>
          <tr><td>Epics</td><td>Table</td><td><code>type:Epic</code>, sorted by WSJF</td></tr>
          <tr><td>Features</td><td>Table</td><td><code>type:Feature</code>, sorted by WSJF</td></tr>
          <tr><td>WSJF Ranking</td><td>Table</td><td>Grouped by Issue Type, sorted by WSJF</td></tr>
          <tr><td>Current Iteration</td><td>Board</td><td>Filtered by current iteration, daily standup view</td></tr>
          <tr><td>My Work</td><td>Table</td><td><code>assignee:@me</code>, personal overview</td></tr>
          <tr><td>Roadmap</td><td>Roadmap</td><td>Timeline by Planning Interval</td></tr>
        </tbody>
      </table>
    </div>

    <p><strong>Path B: Mark as template</strong></p>
    <pre><code>python3 .claude/edpa/scripts/project_views.py template --org my-org --project 1</code></pre>
    <p><strong>Path C: Create from template</strong></p>
    <pre><code>python3 .claude/edpa/scripts/project_views.py create-from-template \
  --org my-org --template 1 --title "New Project"</code></pre>
    <p><strong>Check:</strong></p>
    <pre><code>python3 .claude/edpa/scripts/project_views.py verify --org my-org --project 1</code></pre>

    <h3>1.10 Configure Automations and Status Fields</h3>
    <p><strong>Status fields (4 typed):</strong></p>
    <p><code>project_setup.py</code> automatically creates 4 status fields on GitHub Projects &mdash; one per work-item level:</p>
    <div class="card">
      <table>
        <thead>
          <tr><th>Field</th><th>Applies to</th><th>Workflow</th></tr>
        </thead>
        <tbody>
          <tr><td><strong>Initiative Status</strong></td><td>Initiative</td><td>Funnel &rarr; Reviewing &rarr; Analyzing &rarr; Ready &rarr; Implementing &rarr; Done</td></tr>
          <tr><td><strong>Epic Status</strong></td><td>Epic</td><td>Funnel &rarr; Reviewing &rarr; Analyzing &rarr; Ready &rarr; Implementing &rarr; Done</td></tr>
          <tr><td><strong>Feature Status</strong></td><td>Feature</td><td>Funnel &rarr; Analyzing &rarr; Backlog &rarr; Implementing &rarr; Validating &rarr; Deploying &rarr; Releasing &rarr; Done</td></tr>
          <tr><td><strong>Story Status</strong></td><td>Story</td><td>Funnel &rarr; Analyzing &rarr; Backlog &rarr; Implementing &rarr; Validating &rarr; Deploying &rarr; Releasing &rarr; Done</td></tr>
        </tbody>
      </table>
    </div>
    <p><strong>Engine logic:</strong> <code>status == "Done"</code> = finished. Everything else = in-work. No Blocked/Spillover labels.</p>

    <p><strong>GitHub Projects Automations &mdash; what to enable:</strong></p>
    <div class="card">
      <table>
        <thead>
          <tr><th>Automation</th><th>Recommendation</th><th>Reason</th></tr>
        </thead>
        <tbody>
          <tr><td>Item added to project &rarr; Set status "Funnel"</td><td><strong>Enable</strong></td><td>New issues get a default status</td></tr>
          <tr><td>Auto-add issues from linked repo</td><td><strong>Enable</strong></td><td>Issues from repo automatically in project</td></tr>
          <tr><td>PR merged &rarr; Set status "Done"</td><td>Do not enable</td><td>Premature &mdash; item may still need QA</td></tr>
          <tr><td>Item closed &rarr; Auto-archive</td><td><strong style="color: var(--error)">NEVER</strong></td><td>Archived items disappear from API &rarr; sync.py loses them &rarr; EDPA engine loses data</td></tr>
          <tr><td>Item reopened &rarr; Set status "Implementing"</td><td>Do not enable</td><td>Conflicts with sync &mdash; reopened item may need different status</td></tr>
        </tbody>
      </table>
    </div>
    <p>Configure: project &rarr; <strong>...</strong> menu &rarr; <strong>Workflows</strong> &rarr; enable only recommended ones.</p>

    <p><strong>Granularity</strong> &mdash; all levels share the same modified Fibonacci scale (1, 2, 3, 5, 8, 13, 20, 40, 100) with no fixed per-level cap. Granularity is the team's responsibility during refinement &mdash; if a Story at JS=20+ fits within the iteration, that's fine. AI-assisted work shifts real throughput, and the old human heuristic ("Story max 8") no longer applies.</p>

    <p><strong>Definition of Ready</strong> &mdash; no item enters delivery without:</p>
    <ul>
      <li>Issue Type set</li>
      <li>Parent issue linked (sub-issue)</li>
      <li>Job Size estimated</li>
      <li>BV + TC + RR&amp;OE filled</li>
      <li>Contributors assigned &mdash; <code>contributors[]</code> in YAML
          (auto-detected from PR/commit evidence, or seeded with <code>person</code> + <code>cw</code> share)</li>
      <li>Iteration or Planning Interval assigned</li>
    </ul>

    <p><strong>Recommended Insights charts</strong> (project &rarr; <strong>Insights</strong> tab &rarr; <strong>New chart</strong>):</p>
    <ul>
      <li><strong>Burn-down</strong> &mdash; X: time, Y: item count, Group: Status</li>
      <li><strong>Items by Status</strong> &mdash; bar chart</li>
      <li><strong>Items by Team</strong> &mdash; workload distribution</li>
      <li><strong>Items by Issue Type</strong> &mdash; hierarchy balance</li>
    </ul>
    <p>Insights = real-time dashboards. EDPA engine = governance-grade calculations (derived hours, CW). They complement each other.</p>

    <h3>1.11 Verify Setup</h3>
    <p><strong>Claude Code (recommended):</strong></p>
    <pre><code>/edpa close-iteration    # demo run (no real data)
/edpa sync status        # check sync</code></pre>
    <p><strong>Manual CLI:</strong></p>
    <pre><code># Demo EDPA engine (no real data)
python3 .claude/edpa/scripts/engine.py --demo

# Backlog validation
python3 .claude/edpa/scripts/backlog.py validate

# Project status
python3 .claude/edpa/scripts/backlog.py status

# Sync status
python3 .claude/edpa/scripts/sync.py status</code></pre>

    <h3>1.12 Commit Initial Configuration</h3>
    <pre><code>git add .edpa/config/people.yaml .edpa/config/project.yaml .edpa/config/heuristics.yaml
git add .edpa/
git commit -m "feat(edpa): initial EDPA setup for my-project"
git push origin main</code></pre>
  </section>

  <!-- Phase 2 -->
  <section id="faze-2">
    <h2>Phase 2: First iteration (Week 1-2)</h2>

    <h3>2.1 Iteration Planning</h3>
    <ol>
      <li><strong>Capacity confirmation</strong> — team confirms availability for the iteration</li>
      <li><strong>Story selection</strong> — from the backlog by WSJF order, up to 80% of capacity</li>
    </ol>
    <pre><code># WSJF ranking features
python3 .claude/edpa/scripts/backlog.py wsjf --level feature

# Tree for a specific iteration
python3 .claude/edpa/scripts/backlog.py tree --iteration PI-2026-1.1</code></pre>
    <ol start="3">
      <li><strong>Assignee allocation</strong> — every story must have an assignee</li>
      <li><strong>Backlog update</strong> — <code>iteration: PI-2026-1.1</code> on the selected stories</li>
    </ol>

    <h3>2.2 Daily work</h3>
    <p><strong>Branch naming convention</strong> (CI check in <code>.github/workflows/edpa-branch-check.yml</code>):</p>
    <pre><code># Format: &#123;type&#125;/&#123;ITEM_ID&#125;-&#123;description&#125;
git checkout -b feature/S-200-omop-parser
git checkout -b feature/F-102-anon-engine
git checkout -b defect/D-215-upload-validation
git checkout -b chore/T-050-ci-pipeline</code></pre>
    <p>Allowed types: <code>feature</code>, <code>defect</code>, <code>hotfix</code>, <code>chore</code></p>

    <p><strong>Commit convention:</strong></p>
    <pre><code>git commit -m "feat(S-200): implement OMOP CDM parser"
git commit -m "fix(S-215): validate upload file size"
git commit -m "test(S-201): add unit tests for parser"
git commit -m "docs(E-10): update epic hypothesis"</code></pre>
    <p>The EDPA engine recognizes <code>S-XXX</code>, <code>F-XXX</code>, <code>E-XXX</code> references in commits and PRs as evidence.</p>

    <p><strong>Pull Request workflow:</strong></p>
    <pre><code>git push origin feature/S-200-omop-parser
gh pr create --title "S-200: OMOP CDM parser implementation" \
  --body "Closes #42

## Changes
- Implemented OMOP CDM parser
- Added schema validation

## Testing
- Unit tests: 15 passing
"</code></pre>
    <p>PR review = evidence for EDPA (the reviewer receives CW per their signal).</p>

    <h3>2.3 Sync (automatic)</h3>
    <p>Bidirectional synchronization between GitHub Projects (UI for PM/BO) and item files in <code>.edpa/</code> (Git-native):</p>
    <p><strong>Automatic via GitHub Actions:</strong></p>
    <ul>
      <li><code>edpa-sync-projects-to-git.yml</code> — pulls Projects changes into Git every 15 minutes</li>
      <li><code>edpa-sync-git-to-projects.yml</code> — on push to <code>main</code> with a <code>.edpa/</code> change, propagates into Projects</li>
    </ul>
    <p><strong>Claude Code (recommended):</strong></p>
    <pre><code>/edpa sync pull      # GitHub Projects → item files in .edpa/
/edpa sync push      # item files in .edpa/ → GitHub Projects
/edpa sync diff      # show what would change
/edpa sync status    # sync state</code></pre>
    <p><strong>Manual CLI:</strong></p>
    <pre><code># Pull: GitHub Projects -&gt; item files in .edpa/
python3 .claude/edpa/scripts/sync.py pull

# Push: item files in .edpa/ -&gt; GitHub Projects
python3 .claude/edpa/scripts/sync.py push

# Diff: show what would change
python3 .claude/edpa/scripts/sync.py diff

# Status
python3 .claude/edpa/scripts/sync.py status</code></pre>

    <h3>2.4 Iteration Close</h3>
    <p>At the end of each iteration (after 2 weeks):</p>
    <p><strong>Claude Code (recommended):</strong></p>
    <pre><code>/edpa close-iteration PI-2026-1.1</code></pre>
    <p><strong>Manual CLI:</strong></p>
    <pre><code>python3 .claude/edpa/scripts/engine.py --edpa-root .edpa --iteration PI-2026-1.1</code></pre>

    <p><strong>Outputs:</strong></p>
    <pre><code>.edpa/reports/iteration-PI-2026-1.1/
  edpa_results.json      # Complete calculation (JSON)
  vykaz-alice.md         # Per-person timesheet
  item-costs.xlsx        # Per-item costs (Excel)
.edpa/snapshots/
  PI-2026-1.1.json       # Frozen snapshot</code></pre>

    <p><strong>Gated calculation:</strong> the engine credits Story <code>Done</code> + Feature/Epic/Initiative gate transitions from git history.</p>
    <div class="card">
      <pre><code>Score        = JobSize &times; CW
DerivedHours = (Score / &Sigma;Scores) &times; Capacity</code></pre>
      <p style="margin-top:8px;">CW is a per-item normalized share (&Sigma; across persons on an item = 1.0), computed in <code>detect_contributors.py</code> from evidence (assignee, PR author/reviewer, commit author, issue comment, <code>/contribute</code> directives). The engine consumes CW verbatim.</p>
    </div>

    <p><strong>Invariants</strong> (engine checks automatically):</p>
    <ul>
      <li>Sum of hours per person = their capacity (deviation &lt; 0.01h)</li>
      <li>Sum of ratios = 1.0 (deviation &lt; 0.001)</li>
      <li>No negative hours</li>
      <li>If an invariant fails, the engine reports <code>FAIL</code></li>
    </ul>

    <h3>2.5 Update the iteration plan</h3>
    <p>After closing an iteration, create or update <code>.edpa/iterations/PI-2026-1.1.yaml</code>:</p>
    <pre><code>iteration:
  id: PI-2026-1.1
  pi: PI-2026-1
  start_date: 2026-04-01
  end_date: 2026-04-14
  weeks: 2
  status: closed

planning:
  capacity: 380
  planning_factor: 0.80
  planned_sp: 24
  stories:
    - S-200
    - S-201
    - S-202

delivery:
  delivered_sp: 24
  predictability: "100%"
  velocity: 24
  spillover: []
  unplanned: []
  notes: "First iteration -- full delivery."</code></pre>
  </section>

  <!-- Phase 3 -->
  <section id="faze-3">
    <h2>Phase 3: PI Close (after 4-5 iterations)</h2>

    <h3>Path A: Claude Code (recommended)</h3>
    <pre><code>/edpa calibrate</code></pre>
    <p>Claude Code runs CW calibration, evaluates MAD, and proposes heuristic adjustments.</p>
    <pre><code>/edpa reports</code></pre>

    <h3>Path B: Manual CLI</h3>

    <h3>3.1 Retrospective</h3>
    <p>At the end of a PI (after 4 delivery iterations + 1 IP iteration):</p>
    <ol>
      <li><strong>Walk through auto-detection vs. reality</strong> on 5-10 stories</li>
      <li>For each story compare: who was auto-detected, what CW the engine assigned, does it match reality?</li>
    </ol>

    <h3>3.2 Ground truth for calibration (optional)</h3>
    <p>
      The calibrator runs against a Monte Carlo synthetic corpus (1,000
      scenarios &times; 31,041 records) and searches for MAD-optimal
      signal weights in <code>.edpa/config/heuristics.yaml</code>. A
      <code>ground_truth.yaml</code> is not required &mdash; you can
      run it anytime, even before the first PI close.
    </p>
    <p>
      If you want to calibrate against real records from a PI retro,
      write team-confirmed CW corrections into
      <code>.edpa/data/ground_truth.yaml</code>:
    </p>
    <pre><code>records:
  - person: alice          # id from .edpa/config/people.yaml
    item: S-200
    iteration: PI-2026-1.1
    confirmed_cw: 0.35     # PM/retro-confirmed share (0..1)
    notes: "design review + arch. decisions"

  - person: bob
    item: S-200
    iteration: PI-2026-1.1
    confirmed_cw: 0.65
    notes: "implementation + tests"

  # ... at least 20 records for reliable calibration</code></pre>

    <h3>3.3 Calibrating CW heuristics</h3>
    <p><strong>Claude Code (recommended):</strong></p>
    <pre><code>/edpa calibrate</code></pre>
    <p><strong>Manual CLI:</strong></p>
    <pre><code># Dry-run &mdash; shows proposed MAD reduction without writing
python3 .claude/edpa/scripts/calibrate_signals.py

# Apply &mdash; rewrites .edpa/config/heuristics.yaml with new signal weights
python3 .claude/edpa/scripts/calibrate_signals.py --apply</code></pre>
    <p>Output:</p>
    <pre><code>Phase 1 (random sample): 1000 scenarios, MAD baseline = 0.0861
Phase 2 (coordinate descent): MAD calibrated = 0.0805 (-6.5%)
Calibrated weights:
  assignee:       4.00
  pr_author:      3.40
  commit_author:  2.78
  pr_reviewer:    2.25
  issue_comment:  1.14</code></pre>

    <p><strong>MAD interpretation (Mean Absolute Deviation):</strong></p>
    <div class="card">
      <table>
        <thead>
          <tr><th>MAD</th><th>Rating</th><th>Action</th></tr>
        </thead>
        <tbody>
          <tr><td>&lt; 0.03</td><td style="color:var(--gn)">Excellent</td><td>No change</td></tr>
          <tr><td>0.03 - 0.06</td><td style="color:var(--cy)">Good</td><td>Minor corrections (optional)</td></tr>
          <tr><td>0.06 - 0.10</td><td style="color:var(--yl)">Acceptable</td><td>Consider recalibrating signal weights</td></tr>
          <tr><td>&gt; 0.10</td><td style="color:var(--rd)">Poor</td><td>Calibration required</td></tr>
        </tbody>
      </table>
    </div>

    <h3>3.4 Planning the next PI</h3>
    <ol>
      <li><strong>New epics/features</strong> — add as files into <code>.edpa/backlog/epics/</code> and <code>.edpa/backlog/features/</code></li>
      <li><strong>WSJF prioritization:</strong> <code>python3 .claude/edpa/scripts/backlog.py wsjf</code></li>
      <li><strong>Capacity planning</strong> — update <code>.edpa/config/people.yaml</code></li>
      <li><strong>Update <code>.edpa/config/edpa.yaml</code></strong> — new PI, iterations, dates</li>
    </ol>
  </section>

